When the system is booted, the proxy services register themselves and the serviceRegistered trap will always be sent, followed by the serviceUp trap. The trap will be sent when the service is unregistered. This trap is normally sent upon system shutdown or when a proxy service is terminated in the normal manner. A proxy service is not unregistered when it abnormally terminates and subsequently restarts, hence, the serviceUnregistered trap is not sent in this case.

indeterminate(1) critical(2) major(3) minor(4) warning(5) cleared(6)

This trap is sent when the software watchdog reinitializes itself and its configuration may have been altered. It is sent for the first time upon system bootup, when the software watchdog is started. Subsequently, in the unusual case when the software watchdog abnormally terminates and is restarted, this trap is also sent. In addition, if the SIGHUP hangup signal is sent to ask the software watchdog to re-read the configuration file, and the configuration is altered, the watchdogColdStart trap is sent.

watchdogColdStartTrapSeverity %parm[#1]%;

indeterminate(1) critical(2) major(3) minor(4) warning(5) cleared(6)

Watchdog reinitializes itself and its configuration is unaltered. This occurs if the SIGHUP hangup signal is sent to ask the software watchdog to re-read the configuration file when the watchdog is up and running, but the modification time of configuration file is unchanged from the previous time it is read.
